  "prompt": "How was communication before the cell phone became widespread?",
  "response": "Before cell phones became widespread in the late 1990s and early 2000s, people used several communication methods:\n\n1. Landline telephones\n- Home and office phones\n- Corded and cordless phones\n- Limited to specific locations\n\n2. Public payphones\n- Available in streets, airports, and other public spaces\n- Used when away from home or office\n\n3. Postal mail\n- Traditional letter writing\n- Postcards\n- Slower communication method\n\n4. Telegrams\n- Quick messaging for urgent communications\n- Expensive and limited\n\n5. Pagers/Beepers\n- Received numeric or short text messages\n- Popular in 1980s and early 1990s\n\n6. Fax machines\n- Sent printed documents over phone lines\n- Used in business communication\n\n7. Landline answering machines\n- Recorded messages when no one was home\n- Left voice messages\n\n8. Face-to-face communication\n- More prevalent\n- Personal interactions more common\n\n9. Business communication\n- Office phones\n- Intercom systems\n- Scheduled meetings\n\n10. Early mobile car phones\n- Expensive\n- Limited coverage\n- Bulky equipment\n\nThese methods were less convenient and flexible compared to modern cell phone communication.",
